N = (0,0);
M = (2,0);
L = (2,-sqrt(21));
draw(L--M--N--L);
draw(rightanglemark(L,M,N,10));
label("$M$",M,NE);
label("$L$",L,SE);
label("$N$",N,NW);
label("$2$",(N+M)/2,NW);
label("$\sqrt{21}$",(M+L)/2,E);
[/asy]

Because this is a right triangle, $\sin L = \frac{MN}{LN}.$

Using the Pythagorean Theorem, we find that $$LN = \sqrt{MN^2 + LM^2} = \sqrt{4 + 21} = 5.$$Then $\sin L = \boxed{\frac{2}{5}}$.

We can perform this addition concisely in columns, though we have to "carry" a digit to the leftmost column because $3+8=11,$ which is greater than $10:$ \[
\begin{array}{@{}c@{\;}c@{}c@{}c@{}c}
& 1 & & \\
& 4. & 3 & \\
+ & 3. & 8 & 8
\\ \cline{1-4}
& 8. & 1 & 8 \\
\end{array}
\] The answer is $\boxed{8.18}$.

Since $\sin \angle DBC = \frac{3}{5},$ we can assume that $CD = 3$ and $BD = 5.$  Then by Pythagoras, $BC = 4.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

B = (0,0);
C = (4,0);
D = (4,3);
A = (4,6);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--D);

label("$A$", A, NE);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, E);

label("$3$", (C + D)/2, E);
label("$3$", (A + D)/2, E);
label("$4$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$5$", interp(B,D,0.75), NW);
[/asy]

